  "text": "2+ and Nuclear Factor Kappa B (NF-B) Activation. There are multiple studies with different conclusions regarding whether NF-B is protective or detrimental for heart function although its important role in cardiac pathology [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] has been demonstrated. This disagreement is not surprising considering the complexity of NF-B signaling that involves multiple components and regulation at several steps. Furthermore, NF-B is a pleiotropic transcription factor that receives signals from multiple pathways including different important modulators of cardiac remodeling. To asses a possible direct role of intracellular Zn 2+ on NF-B, we tested the effect of external ZnCl 2 incubation (10 M) of heart homogenates from both control and diabetic groups rats for 20-30 min at 37 ∘ C, similar to previous section. As can be seen from Figures 7(a) and 7(b) , total protein level of NF-B was not affected with 10 M ZnCl 2 incubation of left ventricular heart homogenates from both control and diabetic group rats. However, the activation levels of NF-B in both group rat heart homogenates were significantly increased (∼3-fold in both groups) after ZnCl 2 incubations. This last data further supports the hypothesis that although cardiac remodeling is associated with increased oxidative stress, inflammation, and activation of hormonal systems under hyperglycemia, increased intracellular ZnCl 2 -mediated NF-B activation seems to be a distinct fact among the others under high Zn 2+ exposure of heart.",
